        <h1 class="entry-title">Quantifying Social Behaviour Across Time</h1>
        <p><strong>Social Metrics</strong><p>
        <p>Is it possible to quantify social behaviour?</p>
        <p>I recently graduated from the University of Waterloo, and I was curious to see how my social life changes as time goes on. I wanted to find a way to quantify my social relationships with different people, but most of all, I wanted to see if I would slowly become less social as the change from University to real life impacted me. So I decided to keep a personal log of "Social Encounters" that I would be able to use to quantify my relationships. This daily log would have to contain the enough variables to hold meaningful data, while being simple enough for daily input to not become tedious. I settled on three variables: name, duration of encounter, and date.</p>
        <center><%= image_tag("encounterlog1.png", :class => "img-responsive pull-right") %></center>
        <p>If I spent time with Peter, Katherine, and Kevin for 4 hours, I would input 4 hours for each person that date. I would assess my "socialness" as the total number of hours (12) divided by the number of people seen that day (3) and would come up with 4 as my "social metric".</p>
        <p>I immediately ran into some inherent problems. Consider the following comparison.</p>
