        <h1 class="entry-title">Profiting from the&nbsp;Prophets</h1>
        <p><strong>Security Analyst Recommendations and Stock Returns</strong></p>
        <p>In their paper &#8220;Can Investors Profit from the Prophets?&#8221;, Brad Barber, Reuven Lehavy, Maureen McNichols and Brett Trueman investigate whether investors can profit from publicly available recommendations of security analysts.</p>
        <p>Academic Theory and Wall Street practice are clearly on opposing ends of this issue. Academically, investors should not be able to profit on publicly available information such as earnings reports or analyst recommendations (returning to the market efficiency debate). In practice, research firms and investment banking companies spend a great amount of resources generating analyst recommendations, under the assumption that they will be able to utilize them to create consistent abnormal profits. This paper aims to answer the simple question: Can we profit off publicly available security analyst recommendations?</p>
        <p>Barber et al. do this by using trading strategies of purchasing stocks with the most favourable recommendations by analysts, as well as shorting stocks with the least favourable recommendations by analysts. Over the 1986 to 1996 period, their portfolio ended up with abnormal returns of at least 4 percent (4.13 and -4.91). However, their investment strategies requires a great deal of trading, and with that, high transaction costs. After accounting for those transaction costs, they find that none of their strategies generate an abnormal net return that is reliably greater than zero. This suggests that there are market inefficiencies, however they are not easily exploitable by traders, allowing these inefficiencies to continue to exist.</p>
        <p>I decided to conduct my own research with a couple of colleagues, to see if we could profit off security analysts recommendations in a more recent time period (2008 to 2012, as opposed to 1986 to 1996).</p>
        <p>We extracted historical Bloomberg data from January 2008 to December 2012 on the firms listed in the S&amp;P 500, as of the beginning of our time period. Our main variable was Analyst Ratings, which is the consensus average analyst ratings for one firm, on one date, for many different analysts, based on a range from 1 to 5 (1 being a sell recommendation, 5 being a buy recommendation). Any missing dates in our data set was assumed to take the value of the previous available date for analyst ratings, assuming no new information for the firm is available.  We ended up with just under 1825 points of data for each of the 500~ firms in the S&amp;P 500. We used this to construct our portfolio, which we would hold for 5 years.</p>
        <%= image_tag("profitfromprophets11.png", :class => "img-responsive pull-right") %>
        <p>To decide which companies we would include in our portfolio, we opted to use the top quartile of firms, based on our consensus analyst ratings variable. We thought this would represent the &#8216;top picks&#8217; of a majority of analysts, and would yield the greatest returns. One thing to note is that during this time period, we had a great dip in the market and subsequent upswing, so the average analyst ratings during this time period is rather high (around 4), so a majority of firms in our sample size were classified as &#8216;buy&#8217;. We chose the greatest amongst these, and value weighted them according to market capitalization values.</p>
        <p>We decided to build 4 different portfolio, solely based on the frequency in which we would rebalance or adjust the companies in our portfolio. Our daily rebalancing portfolio would evaluate the analyst ratings daily, and rebuild the portfolio daily, based on new information coming out on the market (reflected in the changing analyst ratings). Our monthly rebalancing portfolio would do this monthly, our yearly portfolio would rebalance yearly. Our last portfolio would be constructed at the beginning of the 5 year test period, and would not change until the end.</p>
        <p>We ended up with these returns for our cumulative 5 year return.</p>
        <p>As you can see, all four of our portfolio outperformed the SPX (which, netted a negative return due to the state of the market). Unsurprisingly, our daily rebalancing portfolio achieved the highest return, presumably based on the notion that our daily portfolio takes advantage of new market information faster than the rest of our portfolios. Curiously, our year rebalancing portfolio performed better than our monthly rebalancing portfolio. This may be attributed to random chance, or it may indicate that our methodology has some flaws and inaccuracies, as it was not consistent with our original hypothesis.</p>
        <p>Below is the cumulative return of our portfolios, compared to the SPX, on a timeline.</p>
        <%= image_tag("profitfromprophets2.png", :class => "img-responsive") %>
        <p>At a quick glance, you can see that all of our portfolios roughly match the S&amp;P 500 Index in direction and movement, however at all points on our timeline, our portfolios consistently outperform the market. This gives me evidence against the efficient market theory, as according to these results, we were able to outperform the market based on publicly available information, in the form of analyst recommendations. Based solely on the information attained in our study, I would recommend a passive portfolio investment strategy, constructed with the top 125 stocks in the S&amp;P 500 based on consensus analyst recommendation, rotating on a yearly basis.</p>
        <p>However, there are some next steps to our study that have not been conducted.</p>
        <ol>
          <li>No significance test of variables</li>
          <li>Incomplete data set (only considers companies as of January 2008, does not consider companies added subsequent to this date)</li>
          <li>Short time period (needs to consider all states of the economy, not just during a depression)</li>
          <li>The cumulative returns do not take into account transaction costs</li>     
        </ol>
        <p>Despite the list above, I am confident to say that yes, we can profit from the prophets, and this study adds to the vast body of knowledge in the debate for market efficiency.</p>
        <p>You can check out the full study <a href="http://webuser.bus.umich.edu/rlehavy/Published_JF.pdf">here</a>.</p>
        <p> Written by Alan Tran, May 1, 2014 </p>
