        <h1 class="entry-title" id="morethanwordsanchor">More Than Just Words</h1>
        <p><strong>Quantifying Language to Measure Firms' Fundamentals</strong></p>
        <blockquote><p class="muted">Language is conceived in sin and science is its redemption</p></blockquote>
        <p>A paper from Paul C. Tetlock, Maytal Saar-Tsechansky and Sofus Macskassy, published in 2008, asks an interesting question. Can we use the language in news report to predict accounting earnings and stock returns? Academically, we learn that the value of a stock is equal to the expected discounted values of the firm&#8217;s cash flows conditional on investors&#8217; information sets, which include qualitative descriptions of firms&#8217; business environments, operations, and prospects in the financial press. Empircally, we find that movement in stock prices does not correspond to quantitative measures of firm fundamentals. So what&#8217;s going on here? Tetlock et al. turn to qualitative variables to try to explain stock movement.</p>
        <%= image_tag("morethanwords2.jpg", :class => "img-responsive pull-left") %>
        <p>They analyse this by seeing how qualitative information, represented by a fraction of negative words in a widely read financial news column, is incorporated in market valuations. Why use language? One advantage of quantifying language is that it allows us to look at the impact of a wide variety of events, whereas most studies focus on a particular event type, such as earnings announcements or mergers. Another advantage is that news reports are a very important source of information for many investors. Very few investor actually observe firm fundamentals firsthand, and therefore rely on news reports and gain their information second-hand.</p>
        <p>How does Tetlock et al. conduct his study? The data is taken from DJNS and WSJ stories about individual firms in the S&amp;P 500 index from 1980 to 2004, and categorizes each word in the article either positive or negative, based on the Harvard-IV-4 psychosocial dictionary. They hypothesize that the fractional amount of negative words in an article is related to the impact of the news event on that stock&#8217;s value. For example consider the following quote from a January 8, 1999 DJNS article about Microsoft:</p> 
        <blockquote><p class="muted">&#8216;The alleged pricing abuse will only get worse if Microsoft is not disciplined sternly by the antitrust court&#8217; said Mark Cooper, director of research for Consumer Federal of America</p></blockquote>
        <p>Based on the classification dictionary that Tetlock et al uses, the abundance of negative words is consistent with the negative message of the overall story, as well as Microsoft&#8217;s abnormally poor stock returns around the news event.</p>
        <p>So what did Tetlock et al. find? Their main research findings:</p>
          <ol>
            <li>Negative words forecast lower earnings</li>
            <li>Negative words are incorporated in stock prices with a slight delay</li>
            <li>Negative words relating to firm fundamentals are more useful in predicting earnings and returns</li>
          </ol>
                
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
        <p>This means that yes, according to the research conducted by Tetlock et al., we can effectively use news reports to predict stock movements. Using this information, the authors of the paper created a trading strategy revolving around the short-run impacts of negatives words. They show that a daily news based trading strategy would earn substantial risk-adjusted returns in a frictionless world with no trading costs.</p>
        <%= image_tag("morethanwords3.jpg", :class => "img-responsive pull-right") %>
        <p>However the results of the trading strategy are conducted under the assumption of zero transaction costs, which is not entirely feasible in real life. To estimate the effect of transaction costs, they recalculate trading strategy returns under the assumption that the trader must incur a round-trip transaction cost of between 0 and 10 bps.</p>
        <p>The table to the right displays the abnormal and raw cumulative news-based strategy returns under the cost assumptions of 0 to 10 bps in trading costs.  We can see that the trading strategy is no longer profitable after accounting for a reasonable level of transaction costs, for example 10 bps. The study shows us that it is nearly impossible to profit off the negative words found in news reports, less we get rid of transaction costs.</p>
        <p>But some things to consider, the study&#8217;s time period is quite outdated. The financial markets in 1980 look completely different than they do now. Access to information is more available and faster, as technology continues to grow. We may even be able to <a href="https://www.robinhood.com/">completely remove trading costs</a> for retail investors.</p>
        <p>You can check out the full study <a href="http://www0.gsb.columbia.edu/faculty/ptetlock/papers/Tetlock_et_al_JF_08_More_Than_Words.pdf">here</a>.</p>
        <p>Written by Alan Tran, April 28, 2014 </p>
